			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Aamen wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Enjoy it while it lasts.  Soloing is all going bye-bye in the next iteration of games.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
 <img src="images/smiles/icon_question.gif" alt="Question" border="0" /> 
<br />

<br />
Not to be mean, but what games are you looking at to come to this conclusion?
<br />

<br />
Horizons = <span style="font-weight: bold">Very</span> solo friendly. The game itself has a lot of potential, but AE's systems are terrible. If they would actually try to, y'know, <span style="font-weight: bold">fix</span> their engine and net code, and add some higher level monsters, they would have a decent game.
<br />

<br />
EQ 2 = The last I heard on the EQ 2 solo front was that they were planning to limit the time you could solo to 2 hours. A <span style="font-weight: bold">huge</span> backlash ensued. Their community guy retracted the time limit statement and said they were looking into "alternate solutions." That means they realised they will have to allow soloing.
<br />

<br />
WoW = No one knows to what extent Blizzard will support soloing, but they have repeatedly said that WoW will be solo friendly.
<br />

<br />
City of Heroes = Solo instances, 'nuff said.
<br />

<br />
I think what that statement should say is "Forced grouping is going bye-bye."
<br />

<br />
Companies will have to realise that mass-market, casual gamers (their next main target) will <span style="font-weight: bold">not</span> mix with forced grouping. (Read next part.)
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Xanther wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">SOE continues this game because its a money maker.
<br />

<br />
There must be some sort of research or market sampling that leads them to emphasize grouping situations over solo possibilites.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
I think you're arguments are flawed for a simple reason: SOE wants mass-market.
<br />

<br />
If SOE truly wants to make a money-hog game, they have to enter the mass-market. Their EQ ad that ran with LOTR at the theatres proves they know this.
<br />

<br />
The problem is, Ma and Pa Kettle know this is just a game. Sure, they may make friends and may play for several hours a day in the beginning; however, as the addiction wanes, the game only stays on their payroll if they are having <span style="font-weight: bold">FUN</span> !
<br />

<br />
I hate to break it to some of you, but the people who stay with EQ out of loyalty to a guild, EQ friends, etc. are <span style="font-weight: bold">not</span> the mass-market type of audience SOE wants to tap. These are the "hard-core" that are probably into CRPGs anyway. These are the ones who are, generally, in raiding guilds that make up 20% of a servers population.
<br />

<br />
Most people, not all, see EQ for what it is: a game.
<br />

<br />
A horribly addicting game, yes, but still just a game. Those people that continue to play out of some (falsely placed) loyalty to a guild, yet are not having fun, are not how the majority would react.
<br />

<br />
For the mass-market, Sony will have to implement a way for an average person to log in to EQ, earn some XP, and feel they have accomplished something, even with as little as 30 minutes to work with. I think they will at least <span style="font-weight: bold">try</span> to allow this with EQ 2, however, whether they will be successful is up in the air.
<br />

<br />
As to the formation of communities, as I have said, these communities will retain a minority of players. However, the formation of a community will happen around any popular, well-designed, game. Downtime/Setup time will force players to interact with each other more, but communities will form either way.
<br />

<br />
I think Brad McQuaid's quote is correct as pertaining to a subset of players, but not the majority. For proof of this, look to multiplayer games such as Quake, Counterstrike, or Diablo 2. These games have very little downtime for "frivolous chat" and yet still retain <span style="font-weight: bold">huge</span> followings. These may not be the players that "you" want in "your" community, but I guarentee that SOE's marketing suits are trying hard to figure out a way to attract even a hefty percentage of these players. They are doing a terrible job so far, but they are trying (see EQOA on PS2).
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Iblis wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">I think there is a simple economic argument:
<br />

<br />
People forced to group are dependent on social relations in-game.
<br />

<br />
Social relations tie the players to the game in a much stronger degree than gameplay.
<br />

<br />
So a group based game has a much more faithfull customer base.
<br />

<br />
So:
<br />

<br />
Group based game => more money.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Let me show you another, no less valid argument for money making:
<br />

<br />
-----------------
<br />
Casual players and soloers tend to play less than people who constantly group.
<br />

<br />
People who play less tend to hold subscriptions longer (yet at the higher, monthly rate) because they experience less "burn out" time.
<br />

<br />
People who play less time per day cost less bandwidth per day.
<br />

<br />
Less bandwidth per day spent on players + long subscription times at the highest rate = money maker
<br />
-----------------
<br />

<br />
Basically, let's say you have 2 customers who pay $13/month to hook up to your home's electricity system. Customer 1 and Customer 2.
<br />

<br />
Customer 1 stays hooked up 24/7 and, when you go to check your bill, really costs you $15/month. Customer 1 has lots of friends that he tells about you, so they move their service over to you, but they still pay you $13/month and cost you $15/month.
<br />

<br />
Customer 2 only hooks up to your system for an hour a week. Customer 2 costs you $3 on your bill. Customer 2 has <span style="font-weight: bold">more</span> friends than Customer 1 and they all tend to do the same things as Customer 2 do.
<br />

<br />
Now, who would you want to stay your customer?  <img src="images/smiles/icon_biggrin.gif" alt="Very Happy" border="0" /></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
