			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>HeOfManyFals wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Group = more players (paying customers) consuming less content (developer time).
<br />

<br />
It's buisness.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
False.
<br />

<br />
Want proof? Ask your local UberGuild_01, who is currently clamoring for content because they have progressed to the "top." Now, ask RandomCasualPlayer_01 who is still going through zones he's never seen and is having fun.
<br />

<br />
In other words:
<br />

<br />
Solo = more players per land area consuming roughly the same amount of content as that group, but in less time.
<br />

<br />
Solo = less time spent at "progressing" through said content, making content last longer than with said group.
<br />

<br />
Groups eat through monsters much faster than soloers. Solo downtime is inherently longer and that is why groups are inherently better. Therefore, solo players take a lot longer to progress through content.
<br />

<br />
A group of 6 players usually holds a camp of monsters to itself. However, a good camp can support 6 or more soloers easily, due to solo-inherent downtime.
<br />

<br />
You have to remember that I'm <span style="font-weight: bold">not</span> saying soloing is "better" or should be the same XP as grouping, I'm saying that it should be an alternative, if the player so wishes.
<br />

<br />
Giving <span style="font-weight: bold">all</span> your customers options means retaining a higher percentage of them.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
